1
00:00:17,226 --> 00:00:18,560
Jerry.

2
00:00:20,270 --> 00:00:21,396
Jerry, you okay?

3
00:00:21,563 --> 00:00:24,274
-You look a little piqued, man.
-I'm fine, it's, uh...

4
00:00:24,441 --> 00:00:26,944
Ms. Hill wants us to move the Sherwood
into the vault.

5
00:00:27,152 --> 00:00:28,654
Now? It's midday.

6
00:00:28,820 --> 00:00:31,990
I know. She says it's a security threat.

7
00:00:32,157 --> 00:00:34,660
It's all the robberies lately. Heh.

8
00:00:50,384 --> 00:00:52,051
[ALARM BLARING]

9
00:00:52,219 --> 00:00:53,262
That way.

10
00:00:53,428 --> 00:00:55,430
[GUARDS CHATTERING]

11
00:00:57,349 --> 00:01:01,603
Take this thing off me, all right?
I got it like you asked. Here.

12
00:01:02,563 --> 00:01:04,690
Take it off me.

13
00:01:10,112 --> 00:01:13,198
Were you...? Were you bluffing?
Would that thing have detonated?

14
00:01:13,365 --> 00:01:15,325
Violently. Don't worry, though.

15
00:01:15,492 --> 00:01:18,495
You did exactly as I asked,
so it's just unconsciousness for you.

16
00:01:18,954 --> 00:01:19,997
Unconscious?

17
00:01:20,205 --> 00:01:21,748
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLES
&amp; JERRY GROANS]

18
00:01:31,466 --> 00:01:34,636
Might wanna take it easy if you plan
on taking someone off that list.

19
00:01:34,803 --> 00:01:37,347
This is me taking it easy.

20
00:01:38,890 --> 00:01:40,475
So who's the unlucky guy tonight?

21
00:01:40,976 --> 00:01:42,101
OLIVER:
Ken Williams.

22
00:01:42,269 --> 00:01:44,354
His pyramid scheme stole millions.

23
00:01:44,521 --> 00:01:47,941
People didn't just lose their homes,
their lives were ruined.

24
00:01:48,108 --> 00:01:51,111
Why don't you call it in early?
I'm not expecting much trouble.

25
00:02:12,090 --> 00:02:14,384
Felicity. Did you just...?

26
00:02:14,551 --> 00:02:17,846
Computer-override your lock?
Maybe a little.

27
00:02:18,013 --> 00:02:20,849
-What are you doing?
-I pulled up information on Mr. Williams.

28
00:02:21,016 --> 00:02:24,269
Did you know he's a widowed father
of a 10-year-old boy?

29
00:02:24,436 --> 00:02:28,815
I told you, I'm only in this to help Walter,
not to be an accessory to orphaning little kids.

30
00:02:28,982 --> 00:02:30,192
I'm giving him a warning.

31
00:02:30,359 --> 00:02:33,195
Has it occurred to you
you could do some good in the city?

32
00:02:33,362 --> 00:02:36,448
Beyond recovering people's
stock portfolios and saving accounts.

33
00:02:39,201 --> 00:02:42,954
You're not the only one who knows
how to reboot my system.

34
00:02:43,246 --> 00:02:44,289
I made a mistake.

35
00:02:44,456 --> 00:02:46,458
-Getting in my way? I don't disagree.
FELICITY: No.

36
00:02:46,958 --> 00:02:49,336
Signing on with you. Even provisionally.

37
00:02:56,301 --> 00:02:58,303
[SLADE GASPING]

38
00:03:00,097 --> 00:03:03,475
Hey. Hey. Drink.

39
00:03:07,646 --> 00:03:09,147
Tastes like dirt.

40
00:03:09,314 --> 00:03:10,857
You gotta stay hydrated, okay?

41
00:03:11,024 --> 00:03:12,943
Hydration is not my problem.

42
00:03:13,110 --> 00:03:16,571
My problem is getting a bullet
dug out of my arm with a dull blade.

43
00:03:16,738 --> 00:03:18,657
Let me take a look.

44
00:03:21,326 --> 00:03:24,079
-Oh. Ugh.
-Is it infected?

45
00:03:25,204 --> 00:03:27,332
Go figure.

46
00:03:27,499 --> 00:03:29,167
Yeah. Uh...

47
00:03:29,835 --> 00:03:31,753
I gotta stop that before it spreads.

48
00:03:33,672 --> 00:03:36,508
SLADE: When you swing past the drugstore
for those antibiotics...

49
00:03:36,675 --> 00:03:40,721
...you wanna get me a copy of <i>Maxim</i>
or maybe a <i>Sports Illustrated?</i>

50
00:03:41,972 --> 00:03:46,101
Yao Fei had these super herbs back
in the cave that would heal anything.

51
00:03:46,935 --> 00:03:47,978
All right?

52
00:03:48,145 --> 00:03:49,980
I'm gonna go get them.

53
00:03:51,356 --> 00:03:53,358
You're not gonna last an hour out there.

54
00:03:54,401 --> 00:03:57,195
Well, I guess you better hope
I get back in 45 minutes, then.

55
00:04:07,998 --> 00:04:09,624
[DOORBELL RINGS]

56
00:04:11,626 --> 00:04:14,379
MOIRA:
Oh. Thank you for coming.

57
00:04:15,297 --> 00:04:19,926
It is so good to see you, Frank. Mm.

58
00:04:20,719 --> 00:04:22,971
-It's been far too long.
-Yes.

59
00:04:23,138 --> 00:04:27,976
My interests in China
have kept me away more than I'd like.

60
00:04:28,185 --> 00:04:33,523
But with the Undertaking approaching,
I felt a return to Starling City was in order.

61
00:04:34,441 --> 00:04:40,405
Actually, Frank, it's the Undertaking
that I wanted to talk to you about.

62
00:04:41,656 --> 00:04:43,909
I wanna get out.

63
00:04:44,743 --> 00:04:47,037
Is this because of
what happened to Walter?

64
00:04:48,205 --> 00:04:50,957
With Walter. With Robert.

65
00:04:51,249 --> 00:04:54,461
Last week, the vigilante
nearly made my children orphans.

66
00:04:54,628 --> 00:04:56,421
I've reached my limit, Frank.

67
00:04:59,549 --> 00:05:00,801
FRANK:
That's, uh...

68
00:05:02,302 --> 00:05:05,013
...a lot to confide in me, Moira.

69
00:05:05,180 --> 00:05:07,766
Robert did.

70
00:05:08,725 --> 00:05:12,020
I know he reached out to you,
whether I was supposed to know it or not.

71
00:05:14,022 --> 00:05:16,691
He had misgivings.

72
00:05:16,858 --> 00:05:19,486
He sought you out
because he knew you did too.

73
00:05:19,653 --> 00:05:21,947
But then he was murdered.

74
00:05:22,781 --> 00:05:25,617
And that should be a cautionary tale
for both of us.

75
00:05:25,784 --> 00:05:30,205
Yes, I know. And I've gone along with this
for as long as I can stomach it.

76
00:05:32,457 --> 00:05:36,837
We started this to fix the Glades, Frank.

77
00:05:37,003 --> 00:05:39,297
To cure the city, not lay it to waste.

78
00:05:40,173 --> 00:05:43,593
You got into this because of
what happened to your daughter.

79
00:05:45,887 --> 00:05:47,222
Frank...

80
00:05:48,306 --> 00:05:50,475
...what would Amanda want you to do?

81
00:06:05,073 --> 00:06:07,117
Well, maybe we should come back later.

82
00:06:07,284 --> 00:06:09,578
No, maybe we should wait.
This is really serious.

83
00:06:09,744 --> 00:06:12,581
What if her next attack of conscience
leads her to the police?

84
00:06:12,747 --> 00:06:13,957
No, she won't say anything.

85
00:06:14,124 --> 00:06:16,585
I had to make the same calculation
when you found out about me.

86
00:06:16,751 --> 00:06:19,629
Mm-hm. What would you have done
if you were wrong...

87
00:06:19,796 --> 00:06:22,424
...and I decided to make a call
to Detective Lance?

88
00:06:23,925 --> 00:06:25,468
I would've put an arrow in you.

89
00:06:25,635 --> 00:06:27,137
[DIGGLE CHUCKLES]

90
00:06:29,222 --> 00:06:32,267
Really? You really would have done that?
Really?

91
00:06:32,434 --> 00:06:36,229
Hmm. I had a bet going with myself
on how quickly you would visit...

92
00:06:36,395 --> 00:06:39,065
...tell me not to reveal your secret.
Looks like I won.

93
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:41,943
Actually, I was hoping that
I could get you to change your mind.

94
00:06:42,110 --> 00:06:43,445
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY ON TV]

95
00:06:43,612 --> 00:06:47,073
I was worked up on adrenaline last night,
and I didn't exactly put my best foot forward.

96
00:06:47,240 --> 00:06:50,327
I was hoping you'd give me the opportunity
to do that now.

97
00:06:51,036 --> 00:06:53,038
How about you start with Ken Williams?

98
00:06:53,580 --> 00:06:55,832
Did he also enjoy your adrenaline
last night?

99
00:06:56,041 --> 00:06:59,127
No. He returned the money he stole
in time to put his son to bed.

100
00:06:59,294 --> 00:07:01,713
Like I said, Felicity, just a warning.

101
00:07:02,047 --> 00:07:05,884
McKENNA [ON TV]: <i>We'd like to remind the public
we are coordinating efforts with Interpol...</i>

102
00:07:06,051 --> 00:07:08,219
<i>...as the Dodger operates
primarily in Europe.</i>

103
00:07:08,386 --> 00:07:12,140
<i>They have advised us to warn the public
he is considered armed and extremely...</i>

104
00:07:12,307 --> 00:07:14,768
I heard about this guy.
They call him the Dodger...

105
00:07:14,935 --> 00:07:19,564
...because he avoids getting his hands dirty.
He uses hostages to do his stealing for him.

106
00:07:19,731 --> 00:07:22,776
-How?
-Puts a bomb collar around their necks.

107
00:07:22,943 --> 00:07:27,322
Last year, a guy in Madrid didn't steal what
the Dodger told him to. It took his head off.

108
00:07:27,489 --> 00:07:29,991
-Literally.
FELICITY: Now this psycho's in Starling City?

109
00:07:30,158 --> 00:07:31,952
Too bad his name's
not in your notebook.

110
00:07:32,118 --> 00:07:36,748
Not all people that I target are on the list.
Every once in a while, I make an exception.

111
00:07:36,915 --> 00:07:39,709
Hostage-taking jewel thief, for example.

112
00:07:42,087 --> 00:07:44,130
So why don't you help us take him down?

113
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:50,720
He's late.

114
00:07:57,894 --> 00:07:58,937
Never.

115
00:08:10,657 --> 00:08:14,494
I maintain a Swiss account
for financial transactions.

116
00:08:15,161 --> 00:08:16,788
Here's the number.

117
00:08:17,998 --> 00:08:19,040
Thanks.

118
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:22,460
I'll wire you the money.

119
00:08:22,669 --> 00:08:25,171
Assuming I don't misplace the numbers.

120
00:08:25,380 --> 00:08:28,758
My bookkeeping method is a little sloppy.

121
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:30,802
Really? Heh.

122
00:08:30,969 --> 00:08:35,306
Clearly, you're under the impression that
you can have the Sherwood ruby for a steal.

123
00:08:35,473 --> 00:08:38,727
Well, you're new here in town.

124
00:08:39,144 --> 00:08:41,896
We're not as refined in Starling City.

125
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:44,149
I am getting that impression.

126
00:08:45,400 --> 00:08:46,985
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

127
00:08:50,321 --> 00:08:51,364
[DODGER CLEARS THROAT]

128
00:08:51,531 --> 00:08:52,574
DODGER:
Don't worry...

129
00:08:52,907 --> 00:08:54,576
...your men are merely unconscious.

130
00:08:56,244 --> 00:09:00,957
In about 17 minutes, they'll wake up with the
ability to tell every other fence in this town...

131
00:09:01,249 --> 00:09:03,877
...that I am not to be trifled with.

132
00:09:04,085 --> 00:09:05,503
[STAMMERS]

133
00:09:05,670 --> 00:09:06,755
What about me?

134
00:09:07,505 --> 00:09:08,631
Uh...

135
00:09:09,632 --> 00:09:11,176
[GUNSHOT]

136
00:09:11,342 --> 00:09:13,219
What about you, indeed.

137
00:09:14,179 --> 00:09:18,391
So to catch this guy we need to either figure
out where he is or where he's gonna be.

138
00:09:18,558 --> 00:09:22,687
This really how you guys figure out how to
get your target? Over burgers and shakes?

139
00:09:22,854 --> 00:09:26,983
Sorry it took me so long. I'm waiting on
a bunch of particularly rowdy customers.

140
00:09:27,192 --> 00:09:28,276
[ALL SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

141
00:09:28,443 --> 00:09:29,944
You need me to handle that?

142
00:09:30,111 --> 00:09:32,739
I appreciate it, but I'm a pro by now.

143
00:09:32,906 --> 00:09:34,699
I'll be here if you need me.

144
00:09:37,535 --> 00:09:39,162
Girlfriend?

145
00:09:39,329 --> 00:09:41,206
No, no, that's my sister-in-law.

146
00:09:42,415 --> 00:09:45,919
-Sort of.
-Carly was married to Dig's brother.

147
00:09:46,211 --> 00:09:47,712
And he passed away.

148
00:09:49,089 --> 00:09:52,634
-Well, looks like she's hot for you.
-Ah. Can we get back to crime-fighting?

149
00:09:52,801 --> 00:09:55,428
Actually, I was thinking
you probably should ask her out.

150
00:09:55,595 --> 00:09:56,638
-Really?
OLIVER: Mm-hm.

151
00:09:56,805 --> 00:09:58,932
I'll do that five minutes
after you ask out McKenna.

152
00:09:59,099 --> 00:10:02,393
Ooh, the detective on the Dodger case.
You have a thing for her?

153
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:04,479
-Uh...
DIGGLE: Yes.

154
00:10:04,646 --> 00:10:06,731
[OVER SPEAKERS]
<i>This is way too hard</i>

155
00:10:06,898 --> 00:10:08,566
I don't see you asking Carly out.

156
00:10:12,779 --> 00:10:16,825
Felicity, this guy,
he's targeting a very specific type of jewel.

157
00:10:16,991 --> 00:10:18,952
We figure out why...

158
00:10:19,119 --> 00:10:21,162
...and that'll give us the how to catch him.

159
00:10:21,329 --> 00:10:22,539
-I have an idea.
OLIVER: Mm-hm.

160
00:10:23,832 --> 00:10:27,001
Your crush object with a badge said
they were working with Interpol.

161
00:10:27,168 --> 00:10:29,254
-Yeah.
FELICITY: Why don't I work up a little tech...

162
00:10:29,420 --> 00:10:33,216
...you distract her with a little flirty-flirt,
slip said tech onto her phone...

163
00:10:33,383 --> 00:10:36,845
...it'll turn it into a microtransmitter and,
boom, we'll learn everything she knows.

164
00:10:37,011 --> 00:10:38,138
Hmm.

165
00:10:38,805 --> 00:10:42,267
-It's not how I typically get my information.
-How do you typically do it?

166
00:10:42,433 --> 00:10:46,062
I find the person and then I put
the fear of God into them until they talk.

167
00:10:47,313 --> 00:10:48,857
But we can try your way.

168
00:10:49,357 --> 00:10:52,110
You know, Carly, I don't want this to, um...

169
00:10:52,694 --> 00:10:55,613
You know, to come off weird or anything,
it's just...

170
00:10:55,780 --> 00:10:59,784
<i>I never wanted to stop
Because I don't wanna start all over</i>

171
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:01,619
Would you like to have dinner?

172
00:11:01,786 --> 00:11:03,371
How about tonight?

173
00:11:03,538 --> 00:11:04,873
-Tonight?
CARLY: What...

174
00:11:05,456 --> 00:11:07,000
...we haven't waited long enough?

175
00:11:07,250 --> 00:11:11,796
<i>All that I want
All that I want</i>

176
00:11:13,756 --> 00:11:17,635
Mm. Who knew street meat
could taste so good?

177
00:11:17,886 --> 00:11:20,221
I had a feeling you needed a break
from the office.

178
00:11:20,847 --> 00:11:22,515
Hank was my first client.

179
00:11:22,681 --> 00:11:26,186
I kept his son from being sent away
for a mugging that he didn't commit.

180
00:11:26,352 --> 00:11:29,731
Then how did that not score you
free hot dogs for life?

181
00:11:29,898 --> 00:11:32,942
CNRI gives low-income people
access to the legal system.

182
00:11:33,109 --> 00:11:36,613
Without them,
his son could have gone to prison forever.

183
00:11:36,821 --> 00:11:39,073
I could've gone to prison too.

184
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:42,701
He couldn't afford a dream team
of super-lawyers.

185
00:11:42,869 --> 00:11:46,873
So I'm supposed to feel guilty because
I'm lucky enough to have a rich family?

186
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:48,082
No.

187
00:11:48,249 --> 00:11:49,500
You are lucky.

188
00:11:49,667 --> 00:11:51,753
And hopefully, CNRI will show you that.

189
00:11:52,378 --> 00:11:53,922
Hey!

190
00:11:55,632 --> 00:11:57,342
[HORN HONKS]

191
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:06,725
Give us the purse
and we won't press any charges.

192
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:19,948
Yeah, you're right.

193
00:12:20,114 --> 00:12:22,367
I really do feel lucky.

194
00:12:23,742 --> 00:12:26,496
LAUREL:
This got snagged as he vaulted over the fence.

195
00:12:26,663 --> 00:12:28,289
Looks like a chain from his wallet.

196
00:12:39,050 --> 00:12:41,636
-I thought you gave up crime-fighting.
-What?

197
00:12:41,803 --> 00:12:44,389
Well, the business with your sister.
I figured...

198
00:12:44,555 --> 00:12:46,891
-Oh.
-...you'd stay out of police precincts.

199
00:12:47,058 --> 00:12:48,268
[CHUCKLES]

200
00:12:48,434 --> 00:12:52,730
Yeah, I... I saw you on the news
and realized that I never thanked you...

201
00:12:52,897 --> 00:12:55,400
...for everything that you did, so...

202
00:12:55,566 --> 00:12:57,610
Thank you.

203
00:12:58,319 --> 00:12:59,445
So you got promoted.

204
00:13:00,071 --> 00:13:01,239
-Major Crimes.
OLIVER: Wow.

205
00:13:01,406 --> 00:13:03,408
And they assigned me to the Dodger case.

206
00:13:03,574 --> 00:13:05,535
He extorts people into stealing for him.

207
00:13:06,828 --> 00:13:09,831
-How's that going?
-Slow.

208
00:13:27,307 --> 00:13:31,477
It was nice seeing you
the last time that I saw you.

209
00:13:31,644 --> 00:13:33,438
Yeah. It was good seeing you too.

210
00:13:33,604 --> 00:13:35,273
It was like old times.

211
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:37,191
Except the PG version.

212
00:13:38,192 --> 00:13:39,527
-How do you mean?
McKENNA: Ha, ha.

213
00:13:39,736 --> 00:13:42,780
Well, you and I always knew
how to have a fun time.

214
00:13:42,947 --> 00:13:44,991
Something that's been
missing from my life.

215
00:13:45,158 --> 00:13:46,409
So how about a drink?

216
00:13:46,576 --> 00:13:47,660
Not now.

217
00:13:47,826 --> 00:13:50,705
Would you maybe...? I'll take you for a...

218
00:13:50,872 --> 00:13:52,707
Would you like to have dinner with me,
McKenna?

219
00:13:52,874 --> 00:13:55,752
McKENNA: Ha, ha.
-I was on a deserted island for five years...

220
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:58,004
...and I am totally out of practice
with this whole...

221
00:13:58,171 --> 00:14:02,300
Mm. Well, dinner would be nice.

222
00:14:02,467 --> 00:14:05,887
In fact, I can make myself free tonight.

223
00:14:07,972 --> 00:14:09,349
-Yeah.
-Great.

224
00:14:09,515 --> 00:14:10,892
So I'll grab you at 8?

225
00:14:11,059 --> 00:14:12,685
That's perfect.

226
00:14:13,353 --> 00:14:14,771
-Okay.
McKENNA: Okay.

227
00:14:14,979 --> 00:14:17,815
-I'm lingering. I'm gonna go.
-Ha, ha. Okay.

228
00:14:37,251 --> 00:14:38,419
[MAN COUGHS]

229
00:14:38,753 --> 00:14:40,546
Who's there?

230
00:14:43,925 --> 00:14:45,551
Help me.

231
00:14:53,351 --> 00:14:54,644
[PHONE DIALING ON RECORDING]

232
00:14:54,811 --> 00:14:56,354
[LINE RINGING ON RECORDING]

233
00:14:56,521 --> 00:14:59,857
LANCE [ON RECORDING]: <i>Lance.</i>
McKENNA [ON RECORDING]: <i>It's Detective Hall.</i>

234
00:15:00,024 --> 00:15:01,859
<i>I have an update on the Dodger case.</i>

235
00:15:02,026 --> 00:15:04,404
<i>A body was found at an art gallery
shot point-blank.</i>

236
00:15:04,570 --> 00:15:07,073
<i>There were three other men,
all rendered unconscious...</i>

237
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:09,158
<i>...by a highly focused electric current.</i>

238
00:15:09,325 --> 00:15:11,160
LANCE:
<i>Same MO as that guard at the museum.</i>

239
00:15:11,327 --> 00:15:12,620
<i>You got an ID on the vic?</i>

240
00:15:12,787 --> 00:15:14,414
McKENNA:
<i>His name is Cass Derenick.</i>

241
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:15,957
Pause.

242
00:15:16,958 --> 00:15:18,209
Who's Cass Derenick?

243
00:15:18,376 --> 00:15:20,336
FELICITY:
Arrest, possession of stolen goods.

244
00:15:20,545 --> 00:15:22,797
Arrest, conspiracy.

245
00:15:22,964 --> 00:15:25,341
Conviction, attempted sale of stolen goods.

246
00:15:25,550 --> 00:15:29,220
This guy's a fence. The Dodger's looking
to unload the Sherwood ruby.

247
00:15:29,387 --> 00:15:31,722
Which means he'll be in the market
for a new fence.

248
00:15:31,889 --> 00:15:34,142
One he hasn't, you know, killed.

249
00:15:34,308 --> 00:15:37,270
So we find the fence
and we find the Dodger.

250
00:15:38,938 --> 00:15:41,774
Anyway, I saw online
that you sell a chain wallet...

251
00:15:41,941 --> 00:15:43,860
...with an eight ball on the chain.

252
00:15:44,068 --> 00:15:47,822
I was wondering if you could give me
a name of one of your customers...

253
00:15:47,989 --> 00:15:49,574
...if I gave you a description.

254
00:15:50,408 --> 00:15:52,952
Yeah, sure, you can call me back.

255
00:15:53,119 --> 00:15:57,623
You and every other used-clothing
and leather-goods store I've called today.

256
00:15:59,083 --> 00:16:00,251
What was that about?

257
00:16:00,918 --> 00:16:04,672
-What's up with the fancy-fancy?
-What...? Oh, um... Heh.

258
00:16:04,839 --> 00:16:08,426
I have a date. Contrary to popular opinion,
I do have a life.

259
00:16:08,593 --> 00:16:11,387
Then why do you seem so nervous?

260
00:16:12,263 --> 00:16:13,306
Is it obvious?

261
00:16:13,473 --> 00:16:15,766
Just be your charming and brooding self.

262
00:16:15,933 --> 00:16:17,727
I mean, girls seem to dig that.

263
00:16:17,894 --> 00:16:20,938
This girl's different.

264
00:16:21,272 --> 00:16:23,608
She knew me before the island,
before I was...

265
00:16:23,774 --> 00:16:25,067
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

266
00:16:25,234 --> 00:16:31,073
It's CNRI. I've gotta take this. I'm working
on a very important purse-snatching case.

267
00:16:31,240 --> 00:16:32,909
Yeah.

268
00:16:33,618 --> 00:16:35,286
Hello?

269
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:38,706
Yeah, he might have been wearing
a red hoodie.

270
00:16:38,873 --> 00:16:41,250
Kind of Abercrombie-looking.

271
00:16:41,417 --> 00:16:44,045
His face, not the hoodie.

272
00:16:44,837 --> 00:16:47,340
Really?
You wouldn't happen to have his name?

273
00:16:47,548 --> 00:16:49,050
[ON STEREO]
<i>You had to sell your gold</i>

274
00:16:49,217 --> 00:16:51,219
Thank you so much.

275
00:16:55,598 --> 00:16:57,683
[LINE RINGS]

276
00:16:57,850 --> 00:17:02,647
Hey, Laurel.
Does your dad still, like, arrest people?

277
00:17:03,231 --> 00:17:04,899
I found the dirtbag.

278
00:17:05,066 --> 00:17:07,652
His name is Roy Harper.

279
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:10,154
CARLY:
I can't remember the last time I was here.

280
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:13,157
It's so beautiful.

281
00:17:13,324 --> 00:17:17,745
Yeah, this was the place
to take a girl in high school.

282
00:17:17,912 --> 00:17:21,082
Hmm, I was never lucky enough
to experience that.

283
00:17:21,249 --> 00:17:24,252
I had braces and terrible bangs back then.

284
00:17:24,460 --> 00:17:25,878
[CHUCKLES]

285
00:17:26,045 --> 00:17:28,047
I'm sure you looked amazing.

286
00:17:28,214 --> 00:17:30,466
I'm glad we finally got around to doing this.

287
00:17:30,675 --> 00:17:32,385
Me too.

288
00:17:34,887 --> 00:17:37,890
You know, Andy set a pretty high bar
when it came to first dates.

289
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:39,100
Hmm.

290
00:17:39,267 --> 00:17:41,227
He faced down armed gunmen for a living...

291
00:17:41,394 --> 00:17:45,231
...but I've never seen him as scared
as he was before that first date with you.

292
00:17:48,150 --> 00:17:49,277
[SIGHS]

293
00:17:49,443 --> 00:17:52,655
Carly, I'm sorry,
that wasn't good first-date etiquette, was it?

294
00:17:52,822 --> 00:17:56,367
To bring up Andy
when we are having a romantic night?

295
00:17:56,534 --> 00:18:00,079
-Probably not.
-Carly, this is difficult and complicated.

296
00:18:00,830 --> 00:18:02,748
It's not like there's a manual, you know?

297
00:18:02,915 --> 00:18:05,835
You know, for a moment...

298
00:18:06,002 --> 00:18:09,630
...I felt like a girl who likes a boy
and nothing else mattered.

299
00:18:09,797 --> 00:18:12,508
Yeah, yeah. Yeah.

300
00:18:12,717 --> 00:18:15,595
If this is too hard for you
or too complicated...

301
00:18:15,761 --> 00:18:19,599
...then please, you know, just get out now
because I've already been hurt too much.

302
00:18:19,765 --> 00:18:22,059
-I'm sorry...
-Can you just please take me home?

303
00:18:24,937 --> 00:18:26,981
[OVER SPEAKERS]
<i>In these little moments</i>

304
00:18:27,148 --> 00:18:29,900
<i>Get your cards out</i>

305
00:18:30,067 --> 00:18:31,402
<i>I am waiting</i>

306
00:18:31,569 --> 00:18:35,615
Mm. No, no, no, it is not possible
for something to be this good.

307
00:18:35,781 --> 00:18:37,408
-Right?
McKENNA: Oh.

308
00:18:41,787 --> 00:18:44,081
-You must have missed soufflés.
-What do you mean?

309
00:18:44,248 --> 00:18:46,459
Five years on an island
away from civilization.

310
00:18:47,043 --> 00:18:48,919
What did you do? What did you eat?

311
00:18:49,545 --> 00:18:52,798
-Where'd you sleep? How did you make it?
-McKenna.

312
00:18:54,175 --> 00:18:55,760
Sorry.

313
00:18:56,135 --> 00:18:57,845
-Didn't mean to drill you.
-It's okay.

314
00:18:58,012 --> 00:19:00,556
I haven't had a conversation
with a guy in a while...

315
00:19:00,765 --> 00:19:03,142
...without it resulting in
me reading him his rights.

316
00:19:03,309 --> 00:19:05,936
Heh. So...

317
00:19:06,103 --> 00:19:08,856
Yeah, but those years,
they must have changed you.

318
00:19:09,774 --> 00:19:11,525
[ARROW PIERCES FLESH
&amp; OLIVER SCREAMS]

319
00:19:11,692 --> 00:19:15,154
From the guy I used to party with
to who you are now.

320
00:19:16,364 --> 00:19:17,406
Yeah.

321
00:19:18,949 --> 00:19:20,743
I had to make some tough choices.

322
00:19:20,910 --> 00:19:22,119
Help me.

323
00:19:22,787 --> 00:19:24,330
You're right.

324
00:19:24,955 --> 00:19:27,166
It changed me.

325
00:19:27,416 --> 00:19:28,459
<i>I am waiting</i>

326
00:19:28,626 --> 00:19:32,797
-What kind of tough choices?
-I don't wanna talk about those experiences.

327
00:19:34,173 --> 00:19:36,258
<i>In these little moments</i>

328
00:19:36,425 --> 00:19:39,220
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

329
00:19:39,387 --> 00:19:40,846
Saved by the cell.

330
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:43,432
Hall. Ahem.

331
00:19:44,100 --> 00:19:47,770
Okay, put what the CI told you
in the warrant application. I'll be right there.

332
00:19:47,937 --> 00:19:49,522
It's work. I gotta go.

333
00:19:53,818 --> 00:19:55,528
Okay.

334
00:20:03,744 --> 00:20:06,914
Felicity, listen. I need you to activate
the bug in McKenna's phone.

335
00:20:07,081 --> 00:20:09,583
I think the police just
got a lead on the Dodger.

336
00:20:10,918 --> 00:20:12,253
Okay.

337
00:20:14,880 --> 00:20:16,132
Who are you?

338
00:20:16,340 --> 00:20:19,218
My name's Alan Durand.
I'm an exchange student.

339
00:20:19,385 --> 00:20:21,512
I was on a fishing excursion with my class.

340
00:20:23,431 --> 00:20:26,350
We got lost and our boat caught fire.

341
00:20:26,559 --> 00:20:29,395
It was some mechanic malfunction.
We had to jump ship.

342
00:20:29,562 --> 00:20:32,648
-When?
-Two days ago.

343
00:20:34,275 --> 00:20:37,570
It was awful. I thought I was gonna die.

344
00:20:38,279 --> 00:20:39,697
[CRYING]

345
00:20:41,073 --> 00:20:45,453
Where are the other students?
Where's the boat's crew? Huh?

346
00:20:48,372 --> 00:20:50,458
I think I'm the only one who made it.

347
00:20:52,209 --> 00:20:54,712
I managed to get to shore.
I thought I was lucky.

348
00:20:54,879 --> 00:20:58,799
What? Somebody found you?
Soldiers or...

349
00:20:59,008 --> 00:21:00,593
Yes!

350
00:21:03,471 --> 00:21:06,557
Yes. They had these masks on.

351
00:21:06,724 --> 00:21:10,895
They attacked me and beat me!
They left me here!

352
00:21:11,061 --> 00:21:12,897
Who are they?

353
00:21:17,485 --> 00:21:19,904
You can untie me at any point, by the way.

354
00:21:28,078 --> 00:21:30,748
DODGER: Nice place you have here.
ABBOTT: Thank you.

355
00:21:30,915 --> 00:21:34,251
Tell me, does every fence
in this town hire muscle?

356
00:21:34,460 --> 00:21:38,214
Heh. I did as soon as I heard
about what you did to Cass Derenick.

357
00:21:38,422 --> 00:21:42,218
Ah, yes, Cass. God rest his soul.

358
00:21:42,927 --> 00:21:44,678
He wasn't a very nice man.

359
00:21:44,845 --> 00:21:47,223
-He tried to steal from me.
-Oh.

360
00:21:47,389 --> 00:21:50,184
I've heard that you have
a better sense of judgment.

361
00:21:50,434 --> 00:21:53,604
And that you'd have no trouble
in moving this.

362
00:21:53,813 --> 00:21:59,026
Well, it's only a recession
for some people.

363
00:22:02,112 --> 00:22:05,616
I take a 15 percent commission
off the top.

364
00:22:06,367 --> 00:22:07,701
Let's call it 12, shall we?

365
00:22:07,952 --> 00:22:11,121
I don't have to remind you
what happened to the last person...

366
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:13,207
...who tried to screw me over.

367
00:22:13,582 --> 00:22:16,168
S.C.P.D. Grab the floor!

368
00:22:18,963 --> 00:22:20,381
[YELLS]

369
00:22:27,221 --> 00:22:29,223
[GUNFIRE]

370
00:22:36,772 --> 00:22:38,148
[ABBOTT GRUNTS]

371
00:22:54,123 --> 00:22:57,668
-Come quietly.
-I'm afraid I'll have to decline.

372
00:22:57,877 --> 00:23:00,421
Then I'm afraid
you won't be going to jail.

373
00:23:11,932 --> 00:23:14,351
[COLLAR BEEPING]

374
00:23:33,037 --> 00:23:36,414
FELICITY:
I heard on the news the Dodger got away.

375
00:23:36,582 --> 00:23:39,168
Hopefully the night
wasn't a complete waste.

376
00:23:39,376 --> 00:23:41,337
Your dates. How'd they go?

377
00:23:41,545 --> 00:23:43,255
-Great.
-Awesome.

378
00:23:43,464 --> 00:23:45,174
You two suck at lying.

379
00:23:45,341 --> 00:23:48,719
The police and I busted it up
before the Dodger could get himself paid.

380
00:23:48,928 --> 00:23:53,724
-Don't change the subject.
-Is your hacker chip still working?

381
00:23:54,725 --> 00:23:56,434
You two are no fun.

382
00:23:57,353 --> 00:23:59,104
Yeah. Still getting a strong signal.

383
00:24:00,064 --> 00:24:01,899
OLIVER:
You should pull up the police records.

384
00:24:02,066 --> 00:24:04,902
-Everything the Dodger's stolen so far.
-What're you thinking?

385
00:24:05,069 --> 00:24:09,406
We know the Dodger has a taste
for a very specific type of antiquity.

386
00:24:11,241 --> 00:24:13,911
Yeah. These all look like
they're from the ominous decade.

387
00:24:14,828 --> 00:24:17,081
The last ten years
of King Ferdinand's reign.

388
00:24:17,581 --> 00:24:20,417
-And she says we have no lives.
OLIVER: Are there any other places...

389
00:24:20,626 --> 00:24:23,504
...that sell or display items
from the ominous thing?

390
00:24:23,671 --> 00:24:25,756
Decade. Not really.

391
00:24:26,423 --> 00:24:28,759
People in Starling City
prefer the Elizabethan era.

392
00:24:28,968 --> 00:24:30,552
OLIVER:
Starling City Cancer Society.

393
00:24:30,719 --> 00:24:33,222
It says they're holding
a fundraising auction tomorrow.

394
00:24:33,389 --> 00:24:37,893
-We could lure him out into the open.
-With what, a fake?

395
00:24:38,102 --> 00:24:40,771
No. The Dodger has a trained eye
for this sort of thing.

396
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:44,525
He's not gonna fall for anything
less than the genuine article.

397
00:24:44,692 --> 00:24:47,111
Where are we gonna get
a rare Spanish antiquity?

398
00:24:47,277 --> 00:24:50,364
You really have no idea
how rich his family is, do you?

399
00:24:58,496 --> 00:25:02,500
Roy William Harper Jr.

400
00:25:05,295 --> 00:25:08,132
-Where's senior?
-Norris Cemetery.

401
00:25:14,722 --> 00:25:17,349
-Sorry to hear that.
-You and an army of bookies.

402
00:25:18,434 --> 00:25:19,893
-[OVER SPEAKER] <i>Can I go?</i>
LANCE: <i>No.</i>

403
00:25:20,060 --> 00:25:22,271
<i>You've been ID'd as a suspect
in a purse snatching.</i>

404
00:25:23,521 --> 00:25:25,190
Quite a résumé you've compiled here.

405
00:25:25,399 --> 00:25:29,153
Petty theft, B and E, robbery, petty theft.

406
00:25:29,319 --> 00:25:31,989
Stolen car. It's nice to change things up
once in a while.

407
00:25:32,156 --> 00:25:34,783
And petty theft.
You got something against banks?

408
00:25:34,992 --> 00:25:37,911
Well, it is hard to run
with one under your arm.

409
00:25:38,078 --> 00:25:40,789
Well, maybe you'll learn
a few new skills in prison.

410
00:25:40,956 --> 00:25:45,085
Look, I don't wanna steal, okay?
I don't have any other choice.

411
00:25:46,045 --> 00:25:49,923
My mother, she has a problem.

412
00:25:50,174 --> 00:25:51,717
Yeah, her son's a moron.

413
00:25:51,925 --> 00:25:53,469
No.

414
00:25:55,345 --> 00:25:56,554
Vertigo.

415
00:26:00,309 --> 00:26:02,936
<i>She got hooked on Vertigo last year.</i>

416
00:26:03,937 --> 00:26:07,941
She kicked it,
but I guess she'd done enough that...

417
00:26:11,737 --> 00:26:13,530
...it messed her up.

418
00:26:13,781 --> 00:26:14,823
Hmm.

419
00:26:15,866 --> 00:26:17,534
She hasn't been the same.

420
00:26:17,701 --> 00:26:22,539
And her medical bills... Look, I'm just trying
to help her get out from under.

421
00:26:25,542 --> 00:26:29,379
Look, we're not privileged enough
to have as much as other people, okay?

422
00:26:29,587 --> 00:26:31,256
Fine.

423
00:26:32,966 --> 00:26:36,970
Let him go. It's just a damn purse, right?

424
00:26:45,771 --> 00:26:49,233
They'll meet with you.
It has been arranged.

425
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:55,781
Thank you for this. There's one more thing
I need you to do for me.

426
00:26:55,989 --> 00:26:59,243
Malcolm's the only one who knows
where Walter's being kept.

427
00:27:00,577 --> 00:27:02,871
I just need a clue.

428
00:27:03,872 --> 00:27:05,958
Some lead to follow.

429
00:27:07,251 --> 00:27:11,463
If our plan works,
I can't let it damn Walter to hell.

430
00:27:14,049 --> 00:27:20,055
No, that's the fate that's in store for us,
I'm afraid.

431
00:27:31,984 --> 00:27:33,986
[ELEGANT CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING]

432
00:27:34,153 --> 00:27:36,155
[GUESTS CHATTERING]

433
00:27:53,172 --> 00:27:56,674
The police are here too.
Your bait's attracted them, at least.

434
00:27:56,842 --> 00:27:59,344
That's not exactly who I'm looking to catch.

435
00:28:09,605 --> 00:28:13,233
So I'm getting a good signal
from the GPS I put in your family's brooch.

436
00:28:13,442 --> 00:28:14,818
I can track it on my phone.

437
00:28:15,027 --> 00:28:18,906
Speaking of, have you given any thought
to what might happen if this doesn't work...

438
00:28:19,072 --> 00:28:22,201
...and the Dodger absconds
with your family jewels?

439
00:28:23,952 --> 00:28:26,079
I'm sorry, that came out very wrong.

440
00:28:26,955 --> 00:28:29,333
Let's just keep our eyes open, Felicity.

441
00:28:33,462 --> 00:28:35,172
DIGGLE:
Hey, isn't that...?

442
00:28:37,758 --> 00:28:38,842
Mm-hm.

443
00:28:39,009 --> 00:28:42,095
I would rather take my chances
with a deadly jewel thief.

444
00:28:42,346 --> 00:28:43,722
DIGGLE:
Right.

445
00:29:00,781 --> 00:29:04,409
Hey, that brooch was donated
by the Queen family.

446
00:29:04,576 --> 00:29:06,870
If you want it,
you're gonna have to bid.

447
00:29:07,079 --> 00:29:10,540
Actually, love, I thought I'd just take it.

448
00:29:16,463 --> 00:29:19,007
I should see if
the security guard's having problems.

449
00:29:19,216 --> 00:29:21,510
Good idea.
I'm gonna go check on the bait.

450
00:29:24,221 --> 00:29:25,764
I think I have a problem.

451
00:29:29,768 --> 00:29:31,561
Get away from me.
If this thing blows...

452
00:29:32,479 --> 00:29:33,605
That's not gonna happen.

453
00:29:34,564 --> 00:29:38,652
The Dodger said if I called the police, he'd...
I'm gonna get decapitated, aren't I?

454
00:29:38,819 --> 00:29:42,864
All right, tracker's on the move.
If I find him, I can get him to disarm it.

455
00:29:43,031 --> 00:29:45,909
-Talk me in. Stay calm.
-Too late.

456
00:29:48,537 --> 00:29:50,914
You can go. Just go, go, go.

457
00:29:56,044 --> 00:29:58,588
Talk to me, Felicity. Talk to me.

458
00:29:58,797 --> 00:30:03,302
Ahem. Heading towards Adams and O'Neil.
He's gotta be in a vehicle.

459
00:30:04,803 --> 00:30:07,222
Hey, I need your bike.

460
00:30:07,431 --> 00:30:08,849
-Are you kidding me?
OLIVER: No.

461
00:30:09,057 --> 00:30:10,851
[GRUNTS]

462
00:30:15,230 --> 00:30:16,565
[ENGINE REVS]

463
00:30:22,863 --> 00:30:24,740
OLIVER:
I'm mobile. Where is he?

464
00:30:27,367 --> 00:30:29,661
[HORNS HONK]

465
00:30:30,746 --> 00:30:32,372
OLIVER [OVER PHONE]:
<i>Talk to me, Felicity.</i>

466
00:30:32,581 --> 00:30:35,625
First time anyone's ever been
grateful for traffic cameras.

467
00:30:35,834 --> 00:30:39,129
One block from you. If you cut through
Harris Plaza, you'll end up behind him.

468
00:30:52,434 --> 00:30:53,769
OLIVER:
<i>Where is he now?</i>

469
00:30:53,977 --> 00:30:55,729
FELICITY [OVER PHONE]:
<i>I got him, I got him.</i>

470
00:30:55,896 --> 00:30:57,898
<i>Gray sedan driving north
at the light ahead of you.</i>

471
00:31:01,651 --> 00:31:04,654
Dead ahead. Good. Okay, hard right.

472
00:31:07,157 --> 00:31:08,241
OLIVER:
Got him.

473
00:32:14,766 --> 00:32:16,351
Don't do anything stupid.

474
00:32:17,602 --> 00:32:21,773
I had the foresight to collar up
a particularly inquisitive blond.

475
00:32:21,982 --> 00:32:23,567
<i>I assume she's a friend of yours.</i>

476
00:32:23,775 --> 00:32:26,403
Touch one hair on my head
and she loses hers.

477
00:32:27,612 --> 00:32:29,781
You've got quite the choice to make,
don't you?

478
00:32:29,990 --> 00:32:31,533
OLIVER:
Not this time.

479
00:32:32,451 --> 00:32:34,995
Your median nerve's been severed.

480
00:32:35,203 --> 00:32:37,747
You couldn't push that button
if you tried.

481
00:32:41,877 --> 00:32:43,628
[BEEPS]

482
00:32:45,338 --> 00:32:48,008
-Oh, thank God.
-Why are you doing this?

483
00:32:49,342 --> 00:32:52,596
I'm exactly like you.
I only steal from the rich.

484
00:32:55,223 --> 00:32:56,683
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLES
&amp; DODGER GRUNTS]

485
00:33:01,188 --> 00:33:02,939
I'm not Robin Hood.

486
00:33:03,982 --> 00:33:06,026
DURAND:
I don't know when these men are coming back.

487
00:33:06,193 --> 00:33:08,737
You have to believe me.
Untie me, please.

488
00:33:14,242 --> 00:33:17,871
What? Do you think these men,
they planted me here?

489
00:33:18,038 --> 00:33:20,123
Some kind of trap or something?

490
00:33:21,625 --> 00:33:25,420
Well, why'd they tie you up like that
and then just leave you?

491
00:33:25,629 --> 00:33:27,130
Huh? Why not just kill you?

492
00:33:27,339 --> 00:33:30,467
They were going to.
They got called away at some altercation...

493
00:33:30,634 --> 00:33:32,677
...somewhere else on the island.

494
00:33:32,886 --> 00:33:35,138
If they come back, they will kill both of us.

495
00:33:35,347 --> 00:33:37,807
Please, you have to believe me. Please.

496
00:33:38,850 --> 00:33:41,144
All right, turn around.

497
00:33:42,395 --> 00:33:43,980
Thank you.

498
00:33:49,194 --> 00:33:50,695
Thank you.

499
00:34:06,044 --> 00:34:07,629
I'm sorry...

500
00:34:09,798 --> 00:34:11,049
...but I can't.

501
00:34:11,258 --> 00:34:14,052
What? Why? Why not?

502
00:34:19,516 --> 00:34:21,518
Because I don't know you.

503
00:34:22,519 --> 00:34:24,521
Are you out of your mind?

504
00:34:24,729 --> 00:34:28,942
Please! You can't do this!
You can't just leave me here!

505
00:34:33,530 --> 00:34:36,950
DIGGLE: Last night, all I could think about
was how pissed off Andy would be.

506
00:34:37,117 --> 00:34:40,537
How hurt he would be
if he saw us together.

507
00:34:43,623 --> 00:34:47,794
But that's nothing compared to how he'd be
if I did something to hurt you, Carly.

508
00:34:48,003 --> 00:34:51,089
Believe me when I tell you
that war is easier than dating.

509
00:34:52,716 --> 00:34:55,760
In a war, you act or you die.

510
00:34:56,720 --> 00:34:59,556
No time to think,
no time to second-guess yourself.

511
00:35:01,558 --> 00:35:06,605
Maybe that's your problem.
With me, you're thinking. Not feeling.

512
00:35:09,399 --> 00:35:10,900
DIGGLE:
You're right.

513
00:35:43,516 --> 00:35:45,477
ROY:
How'd you know where I live?

514
00:35:45,644 --> 00:35:47,771
A little thing called the Internet.

515
00:35:48,521 --> 00:35:51,441
Look, can we not do this
with a door between us?

516
00:36:02,369 --> 00:36:04,162
I guess you're not pressing charges...

517
00:36:04,329 --> 00:36:06,706
...because you feel like
you can change my life?

518
00:36:06,873 --> 00:36:10,251
So you can tell your rich prep-school
friends what a saint you are...

519
00:36:10,418 --> 00:36:14,589
-...and how you're helping the disadvantaged?
-You don't know a thing about me.

520
00:36:15,548 --> 00:36:18,051
Thea Queen, trust-fund brat.

521
00:36:18,301 --> 00:36:21,596
Totaled her car,
which she got as a birthday present.

522
00:36:21,805 --> 00:36:24,891
Loves designer labels
and is in the tabloids for partying too much.

523
00:36:25,100 --> 00:36:27,394
Did I leave anything out?

524
00:36:28,311 --> 00:36:29,646
Yeah.

525
00:36:29,813 --> 00:36:33,775
Dead father, missing stepdad,
damaged brother...

526
00:36:33,942 --> 00:36:37,112
...and almost served jail time
for that car accident.

527
00:36:37,320 --> 00:36:40,824
Plus, she really wants her purse back.

528
00:36:43,159 --> 00:36:45,328
You showed some real sack
coming down here...

529
00:36:45,495 --> 00:36:47,831
...the Glades in the middle of the night.

530
00:36:47,997 --> 00:36:50,834
You must not know
the value of a vintage purse.

531
00:36:51,543 --> 00:36:52,794
[SCOFFS]

532
00:37:10,145 --> 00:37:12,689
Don't worry, it's all there, except for these.

533
00:37:14,607 --> 00:37:18,862
-That's a really filthy habit you got there.
-Yeah. Tell me about it.

534
00:37:19,863 --> 00:37:21,364
Hey, can I give you some advice?

535
00:37:22,449 --> 00:37:25,076
First, stay out of the Glades.

536
00:37:25,285 --> 00:37:26,786
And second?

537
00:37:28,037 --> 00:37:31,249
Don't fall for every sob story
a guy like me tells the police.

538
00:37:34,085 --> 00:37:35,587
You have a great evening, now.

539
00:37:54,564 --> 00:37:56,691
Do you ever take time off?

540
00:37:57,734 --> 00:37:59,235
I do.

541
00:37:59,402 --> 00:38:02,697
In fact, last night, I went on a date.

542
00:38:03,573 --> 00:38:05,575
The guy was kind of a jerk.

543
00:38:05,784 --> 00:38:06,910
Really?

544
00:38:08,328 --> 00:38:09,746
He might've had a reason.

545
00:38:13,833 --> 00:38:17,921
McKenna, I didn't just lose
five years on the island.

546
00:38:18,129 --> 00:38:22,634
I lost the part of me
that enjoyed being alive.

547
00:38:25,970 --> 00:38:28,306
Listening to music and, uh...

548
00:38:29,182 --> 00:38:33,561
...eating a soufflé with a beautiful girl.

549
00:38:33,770 --> 00:38:35,688
It's the easy things.

550
00:38:37,065 --> 00:38:42,320
But when you asked me about the island,
it reminded me of all the hard things.

551
00:38:42,529 --> 00:38:47,784
And the hard choices that I had to make
that still stay with me.

552
00:38:48,868 --> 00:38:51,120
Made me question how I can trust...

553
00:38:51,287 --> 00:38:54,791
...and even if I'm worthy of being
with anyone.

554
00:39:10,515 --> 00:39:12,517
You are.

555
00:39:13,893 --> 00:39:15,436
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

556
00:39:15,603 --> 00:39:18,857
Can I take you to a dinner
that I promise not to cut short?

557
00:39:19,023 --> 00:39:20,900
Um...

558
00:39:21,067 --> 00:39:24,112
-Throw in a soufflé and you're on.
LANCE: McKenna.

559
00:39:26,281 --> 00:39:28,783
I'm glad you're still here. Queen.

560
00:39:28,950 --> 00:39:30,493
-Mr. Lance.
McKENNA: I was just leaving.

561
00:39:30,660 --> 00:39:31,661
Is everything okay, sir?

562
00:39:31,870 --> 00:39:36,583
Yeah. I'd like you to work with me
on the vigilante investigation.

563
00:39:36,749 --> 00:39:39,752
Yes, sir. Well, don't worry.
We'll bring him in...

564
00:39:40,003 --> 00:39:41,254
Oh, yeah.

565
00:39:43,172 --> 00:39:44,507
[McKENNA CHUCKLES]

566
00:39:45,300 --> 00:39:49,387
-Uh, ready to go?
-Yep.

567
00:39:49,554 --> 00:39:51,014
McKENNA:
Okay.

568
00:39:56,895 --> 00:40:01,441
Tastes like an ashtray,
but does the job.

569
00:40:04,444 --> 00:40:06,696
I owe you one.

570
00:40:09,449 --> 00:40:11,784
You didn't get into any trouble
out there, did you?

571
00:40:12,243 --> 00:40:13,536
Hmm?

572
00:40:16,706 --> 00:40:19,626
No. Not a bit.

573
00:40:24,172 --> 00:40:26,215
Frank Chen recommended you.

574
00:40:26,382 --> 00:40:28,801
He said you could help us
with our problem.

575
00:40:30,386 --> 00:40:33,556
He appreciates you agreeing
to meet with me.

576
00:40:36,476 --> 00:40:38,686
Anything for a friend.

577
00:40:41,189 --> 00:40:43,107
So how can we be of assistance?

578
00:40:43,316 --> 00:40:44,901
Malcolm Merlyn.

579
00:40:46,736 --> 00:40:48,905
I want you to kill him for me.

